=========================================
C++ noexcept (C++11) - INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is noexcept?
---------------------
noexcept is a C++11 specifier used to declare that a function
will NOT throw exceptions.

Syntax:
void func() noexcept;

Meaning:
- Function guarantees no exception will be thrown.

-----------------------------------------

2. Why noexcept is used?
-------------------------
- Improves performance
- Enables compiler optimizations
- Avoids stack unwinding overhead
- Used in STL optimizations (vector, move operations)

-----------------------------------------

3. Syntax Variants
-------------------
void f() noexcept;          // no exception
void f() noexcept(true);    // same as above
void f() noexcept(false);   // may throw exception

-----------------------------------------

4. Example
-----------
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void safeFunc() noexcept
{
    cout << "Safe function\n";
}

void riskyFunc() noexcept(false)
{
    throw runtime_error("Error");
}

-----------------------------------------

5. noexcept vs throw()
-----------------------
Old C++:
void f() throw();   // no exception (deprecated)

Modern C++:
void f() noexcept;

- noexcept is faster and optimized
- throw() is deprecated

-----------------------------------------

6. Important STL Usage
----------------------
- vector uses noexcept move constructor for optimization
- If move constructor is NOT noexcept → vector uses copy (slow)

-----------------------------------------

7. noexcept with Move Constructor (IMPORTANT)
---------------------------------------------
class A {
public:
    A(A&& other) noexcept {
        // move implementation
    }
};

WHY IMPORTANT:
- Enables efficient vector reallocation
- Improves performance
- Avoids copying large objects

-----------------------------------------

8. What happens if noexcept function throws?
--------------------------------------------
If a noexcept function throws:
→ std::terminate() is called
→ program crashes immediately

Example:
void f() noexcept {
    throw 10;   // terminate
}

-----------------------------------------

9. Compile-time check
---------------------
noexcept(expression)

Example:
cout << noexcept(func) << endl;

Returns:
true / false

-----------------------------------------

10. Conditional noexcept
------------------------
template <typename T>
void func(T t) noexcept(noexcept(T()))
{
}

Meaning:
Function is noexcept only if condition is true.

-----------------------------------------

11. Use Cases
-------------
- Move constructors
- STL containers (vector, map)
- High-performance systems
- Embedded systems
- Exception-safe APIs

-----------------------------------------

12. Interview Questions
-----------------------
Q: What is noexcept?
A: It tells compiler function will not throw exceptions.

Q: What if noexcept function throws?
A: Program calls std::terminate().

Q: Why important in move semantics?
A: Enables STL optimizations like move instead of copy.

Q: Is noexcept better than throw()?
A: Yes, throw() is deprecated.

-----------------------------------------

13. QUICK REVISION
------------------
- noexcept = no exception guarantee
- Improves performance
- Used in move constructors
- Helps STL optimization
- If violated → program terminates
- Replaces throw()

-----------------------------------------

14. ONE-LINE ANSWER
-------------------
noexcept specifies that a function will not throw exceptions and allows compiler and STL optimizations, especially in move semantics and container operations.
